DOCUMENT();    # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros(
    'PGstandard.pl', 'PGML.pl', 'PGchoicemacros.pl', 'PGasu.pl',
    'PGcourse.pl'
);

$r = [
    [
        random(1, 6),
        random(1, 7),
        random(1, 6),
        random(1, 7),
        random(1, 7),
        random(1, 1),
        random(1, 6),
        random(2, 6)
    ],
    [
        random(1, 5),
        random(2, 6),
        random(3, 5),
        random(1, 7),
        random(1, 7),
        random(1, 7),
        random(1, 7),
        random(1, 7)
    ],
    [
        random(3, 5),
        random(1, 4),
        random(1, 7),
        random(1, 4),
        random(1, 7),
        random(3, 5),
        random(1, 5),
        random(2, 6)
    ],
    [
        random(1, 5),
        random(1, 5),
        random(1, 7),
        random(1, 7),
        random(1, 7),
        random(2, 6),
        random(1, 7),
        random(2, 6)
    ],
    [
        random(1, 7),
        random(1, 5),
        random(1, 4),
        random(3, 5),
        random(1, 7),
        random(1, 7),
        random(3, 5),
        random(2, 6)
    ]
];

@freq = map {0} (0 .. 6);
for $j (0 .. 4) {
    for $k (0 .. 7) {
        $freq[ $r->[$j][$k] - 1 ] += 1;
    }
}
$total = 40;

$house_table =
    DataTable($r, align => '|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|', horizontalrules => 1);

@rel_freq = map { $_ / $total } @freq;

BEGIN_PGML

The U.S. Bureau of the Census conducts nationwide sureys on characteristics of U.S. households.  Following are data on the number of people per household for a sample of 40 households.  Construct a grouped data table for these household sizes.

[$house_table]*

Fill in the following table for this data:

[#
    [.Household size.] [.Frequency.][.Relative Frequency .]*{headerrow => 1}
    [. 1 .] [. [_]{$freq[0]} .] [. [_]{$rel_freq[0]} .]*
    [. 2 .] [. [_]{$freq[1]} .] [. [_]{$rel_freq[1]} .]*
    [. 3 .] [. [_]{$freq[2]} .] [. [_]{$rel_freq[2]} .]*
    [. 4 .] [. [_]{$freq[3]} .] [. [_]{$rel_freq[3]} .]*
    [. 5 .] [. [_]{$freq[4]} .] [. [_]{$rel_freq[4]} .]*
    [. 6 .] [. [_]{$freq[5]} .] [. [_]{$rel_freq[5]} .]*
    [. 7 .] [. [_]{$freq[6]} .] [. [_]{$rel_freq[6]} .]*
    [. Total .] [. 40 .] [. 1.]
#]{padding => [0.25, 0.25], horizontalrules => 1}

END_PGML

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
First, count up the number of 1s, 2s, 3s, ... in the table above to create the frequency.  Then, since the total number of observations (households) for this problem is 40, divide the frequency by 40 to get the relative frequency.   The result is:

[#
    [.Household size.] [.Frequency.][.Relative Frequency .]*{headerrow => 1}
    [. 1 .] [. [$freq[0]] .] [. [$rel_freq[0]] .]*
    [. 2 .] [. [$freq[1]] .] [. [$rel_freq[1]] .]*
    [. 3 .] [. [$freq[2]] .] [. [$rel_freq[2]] .]*
    [. 4 .] [. [$freq[3]] .] [. [$rel_freq[3]] .]*
    [. 5 .] [. [$freq[4]] .] [. [$rel_freq[4]] .]*
    [. 6 .] [. [$freq[5]] .] [. [$rel_freq[5]] .]*
    [. 7 .] [. [$freq[6]] .] [. [$rel_freq[6]] .]*
    [. Total .] [. 40 .] [. 1.]
#]{padding => [0.25, 0.25], horizontalrules => 1}

END_PGML_SOLUTION

